Nnñnooooooootttttttt safe

Glue traps are sadistic. They don't actually hurt the animal, no. But they almost always mean death. And it is usually a very slow, agonizing, and frightening process that leaves the animal wallowing in its own urine and feces for days as it starves and dehydrates.

Even if you put the trap somewhere you can regularly monitor it and try to remove the animal from the trap, trying to remove small animal with lots of fur stuck to a glue trap typically results in pain and broken bones in the animal.

I bought a glue trap for my parents house once as a teen. I thought it would be a kinder method than my dad's old snap traps. I ended up having to quickly drown a harmless little mouse (didn't even look like a field mouse... Looked like a neighbor might have lost a pet) because it was so stuck to the trap that I could tell I was badly hurting it no matter where I tried to pull (tail, back, belly, rear hip/legs). That was the first and last glue trap I ever used - because I am not some tiny peckered territorial sadist easily emasculated by tiny rodents.

I use a little tunnel trap (that is also infinitely reusable, unlike these idiotic sociopaths and their disposable glue traps created for psycho animal torturers) on the rare occasion that a mouse finds its way into my home. I have used it once in 5 years of home ownership and the animal was not even scared when I released it (didn't even pee in my trap).

Don't use a glue trap if you have even a tiny fraction of a soul.

Twinkle-toeing and jumping are both horribly stupid moves to be honest. Smaller surface area means higher pressure, it sinks you deeper and quicker at the tip of your foot and the force generated by the forefoot alone is impossible to escape the glue. Jumping is even worse considering how even with both legs you can't generate thrust force stronger than the gripping force of the glue,all you will get in the end is nothing but a face-planting straight towards the floor as the grip force pulls you down.
Should've tried walking through it with only the heels in contact with the glue and not the balls of the feet or toes.

Once i put a giant(not compared to this one) sticky trap and a rat got stuck on it, it ran across the room with the trap and my dog ended up chasing it and getting stuck with the rat at 2 am.

My dog then freaked out and i spent a good 30 minutes chasing him around the house as he was freaking out thinking he was being attacked.

Eventually i pinned him down and called my neighbor with my phone for help as i held him down. Turns out they heard the commotion and came over immediately.

I decided to throw flour on the trap so it would no longer be sticky as i pried my dogs foot off and it worked. The whole 10 minutes i was holding him down waiting for my neighbor the (giant) rat was biting at us but i eventually got them separated and my neighbor disposed of it while i calmed the dog down. The sticky residue took a month to get off of him even though we shaved his hair.

Conclusion: make sure to secure the trap since it is so light that the rat can easily run with it. And use flour or oil if this or something similar happens to you.
